
Kustomize
-------------------------------------------------------------

Kustomize overlays are useful because when you need to
change a Deployment YAML for different environments -- 
for example, Dev and Prod, the changes are usually small 
compared to the entire YAML, which may be large.

These Kustomize overlays allow you to have a common base
and then make modifications for the different environments
only with overlays. Much less error-prone.

Also, everything is done with YAML. No need to learn a new
templating language.



Helm
-------------------------------------------------------------

Complex deployments may require many YAML files. Rather than
deal with each one by hand, Helm Charts give you a higher level 
of abstraction that lets you manage them all at once, so you 
can deploy, upgrade, or roll back a complex deployment very 
much like you might do with installed software.

Here is the structure of a Helm chart:

my-app/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Chart.yaml              # Chart metadata (required)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ values.yaml             # Default configuration values (required)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ charts/                 # Sub-charts / dependencies (optional)
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ templates/              # Kubernetes manifest templates (required)
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ deployment.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ service.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ ingress.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ configmap.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ _helpers.tpl        # Common helper templates
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ NOTES.txt           # Message shown after `helm install`
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ README.md               # Documentation for users of the chart


A simple real example:

web-app/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Chart.yaml
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ values.yaml
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ templates/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ deployment.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ service.yaml
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ NOTES.txt
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ README.md


Chart.yaml
{
  apiVersion: v2
  name: web-app
  description: A simple web application
  type: application
  version: 1.0.0          # Chart version
  appVersion: "1.2.3"     # Version of the application itself
}


values.yaml
{
  replicaCount: 2

  image:
    repository: nginx
    tag: "alpine"
    pullPolicy: IfNotPresent

  service:
    type: ClusterIP
    port: 80

  resources:
    limits:
      cpu: 200m
      memory: 256Mi
    requests:
      cpu: 100m
      memory: 128Mi
}


templates/deployment.yaml
{
  apiVersion: apps/v1
  kind: Deployment
  metadata:
    name: {{ .Release.Name }}-web
  spec:
    replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}
    selector:
      matchLabels:
        app: {{ .Release.Name }}
    template:
      metadata:
        labels:
          app: {{ .Release.Name }}
      spec:
        containers:
        - name: web
          image: "{{ .Values.image.repository }}:{{ .Values.image.tag }}"
          ports:
          - containerPort: 80
          resources:
            {{- toYaml .Values.resources | nindent 10 }}
}


Now when someone uses this chart, they can override things:

  helm install my-web ./web-app \
    --set replicaCount=3 \
    --set image.tag=1.25 \
    --set resources.limits.memory=512Mi

Or they can supply an entire override file:

  helm install my-web ./web-app -f values-prod.yaml

When Helm renders templates/deployment.yaml, it effectively does something 
like this behind the scenes:

// Helm creates this data structure
dot := struct {
    Release struct {
        Name      string
        Namespace string
        Revision  int
        // ...
    }
    Values  map[string]interface{}   // from values.yaml + overrides
    Chart   map[string]interface{}   // from Chart.yaml
    // ...
}{
    Release: { Name: "my-web-app", ... },
    Values:  { replicaCount: 3, image: { tag: "alpine" }, ... },
    Chart:   { Name: "web-app", Version: "1.0.0", ... },
}

Then it renders your template using this data.

Expression                               Where the value comes from

{{ .Release.Name }}                      The release name you gave in helm 
                                         install / helm upgrade

{{ .Values.xxx }}                        values.yaml + any overrides you pass 
                                         on the command line

{{ .Chart.Version }}                     The version: field in Chart.yaml

{{ .Release.Namespace }}                 The namespace the release is being 
                                         installed into



